caption: Amazing hidden gem in DuPont Circle! First off, they’re to-go packaging is some of the best I’ve seen during the Pandemic (very carefully packed and arranged). Second, they didn’t skimp on the burrito filling. I actually thought I might’ve ticked the box for “extra meat” by accident when I ordered, but they just give you that much as a base! Everything was so flavorful and satisfying, I’m definitely going to be a repeat customer!

The Well Dressed Burrito (or "The Friendly Burrito" to many local denizens) is a wonderfully-kept secret just off the circle in Dupont. Traditional Tex-Mex fare done perfectly, with generous sides and very reasonable prices. An enormous chimichanga with rice and beans will run you around nine dollars and is a true treat. Definitely give this gem a try if you're in the area (just be careful walking down the alley!).
I come here frequently for lunch.  The food is tasty. The portions are large. And its an affordable lunch. 5/5.

Quick and friendly service! Best for take-out since seating is very limited, but I think it adds to the charm of the place. Wonderful gluten free (gf) and vegetarian as well with no loss of flavor. Just about anything on the menu can be made gluten free/conscious for no extra charge. The empanadas were great, even flourless, and were stuffed with chicken and only totaled $8 as a weekly special. Hot sauce is not that hot but very flavorful. A must visit for a quick meal!

I went here once about 5 years ago, but moved away so I wasnt able to visit again. The first time i ordered El Gordo because who wouldn't want a burrito the size of an entire to go container? It was extremely delicious with the sauteed veggies. I was able to go back again and it was just as good as I remembered. This time I ordered a basic taco salad, but the atmosphere and amazing mural view makes any meal here more than basic. This is a must try for anyone visiting, but I must warn you... get there as soon as it opens because it fills up quick! At first I couldn't figure out how a restaurant that is hidden down an alley way between the tall skyscrapers of dc and only open for 2 hours, 5 days a week could ever stay in business.. then I got my food a few minutes later and found out while tryicing to squeeze by the crown that is lining out the door!

Pros: no frills, in a great location for a work time lunch drop-in, inexpensive, wide menu (not just burritos!), super friendly if not somewhat pushy employees, and quick food prep.  Cons: extremely small seating space, bland food. Maybe this experience is limited to me because I'm a vegetarian and got the sauteed vegetable burrito, but there's something about a squash / carrot / olive burrito that seems off to me. I'm sure the bean & cheese would have hit the spot better.  If you're in the area and need a quick and cheap meal, this is definitely the best option around.

There should never be any argument that this restaurant is not significantly better than Chipotle, California Tortilla, Moes, and any other fast food Latin-esque restaurant. Their sauces have tons of flavor, and the cheese is actually cheesy and not just a weird white, gelatinous substance. They actually have mole sauce. My wife says they have great Guacamole. I read from another post that their meat didn't have tons of flavor, and I would say I mostly agree. But the sauces made up for it.  I did not give them five stars because I waited 15 minutes in a semi-crowded area for my food. They said this was the busiest day of the year for them in terms of catering. I can accept that and I will go back again. Their location is also kind of awkward. They are in an alley, and their door swings open in sort of a dangerous manner. There's not a lot of room to sit down, nor are there windows. I was pleasantly surprised by a lack of ventilation issues.  But damn, that food was magnificent.

Best lunch spot in DC - cheap, plentiful, good quality, and there's a constantly changing menu.  The namesake "Well Dressed Burrito" is a daily special, and while there are some favorites that seem to make it back every week, there's plenty of variety.  If that isn't your thing, there's a daily salad which also rotates, and "The Grill" - a slightly more expensive ($11-$13) entree that really showcases WDB's roots as a legit catering company.  Case in point - the rootbeer braised short rib is divine.  That's just the rotating daily menu though - there's a staple, always-available menu of items where you can get standard Tex-Mex fare like enchiladas, normal burritos, chimichangas, etc.  If you arrive at opening, there's not much of a wait, but around 12:10 you can expect to spend at least a few minutes waiting for your food, and at its worst it could be 20 minutes.  That being said, it's indoors and air conditioned, so even in the summer heat it's not that bad.  Special holiday events bring treats like in-store Easter egg hunts, free margarita shots (for those of age) and other perks.  And let's not forget the people - it's an incredibly friendly bunch of people there, so don't be afraid to make a new friend or two.

I got the Well Dressed Burrito which was good but not amazing. Everyone always gives Chipotle trash for being a chain and this and that but their ingredients hands down, always taste fresher... Well Dressed Burrito is no exception. The Burrito was very tasty but it just didn't feel as crisp and juicy. The steak was slightly overcooked although it had a delicious marinade on it. (Chipotle cooks their steak to perfection, still a little pink, so it's very juicy). The guacamole is good but not great. My friends and myself agree Chipotle has some of the best guacamole we've ever had anywhere... and it doesn't matter the location. There is a reason Chipotle won "The Washingtonian" Best Eats under $10. WDB goes get a bonus point for value. The burritoes there are pretty cheap. And overall I do like it and would recommend to those who have not yet tried. On a side note the place was almost empty and it took me 10 minutes to get a burrito... That's pretty slow for a "carry-out" place
